The paper presents a new paradigm of learning partial differential equations from small data using machine learning techniques. The methodology relies on Gaussian processes, a powerful tool for probabilistic inference over functions, which is commonly used in the field of machine learning. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper deals with the problem of system identification, which falls under the category of numerical analysis (cs.NA). The paper also discusses the application of the proposed methodology to a variety of scientific domains, including physics, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of computational physics (cs.SI). Furthermore, the paper proposes a new direction for designing learning machines, which may fall under the category of computer engineering (cs.CE). Finally, the paper uses probabilistic inference to strike a balance between model complexity and data fitting, which is a common technique in the field of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
